U.S. Communications Hacked
--------------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/tech/cybersecurity/u-s-w=
iretap-systems-targeted-in-china-linked-hack-327fc63b ) :

A cyberattack tied to the Chinese government penetrated the networks of a s=
wath of U.S. broadband providers, potentially accessing information from sy=
stems the federal government uses for court-authorized network wiretapping =
requests. For months or longer, the hackers might have held access to netwo=
rk infrastructure used to cooperate with lawful U.S. requests for communica=
tions data, according to people familiar with the matter, which amounts to =
a major national security risk. The attackers also had access to other tran=
ches of more generic internet traffic, they said.

Verizon Communications, AT&T and Lumen Technologies are among the companies=
 whose networks were breached by the recently discovered intrusion, the peo=
ple said. The widespread compromise is considered a potentially catastrophi=
c security breach and was carried out by a sophisticated Chinese hacking gr=
oup dubbed Salt Typhoon. It appeared to be geared toward intelligence colle=
ction, the people said.

The surveillance systems believed to be at issue are used to cooperate with=
 requests for domestic information related to criminal and national securit=
y investigations. Under federal law, telecommunications and broadband compa=
nies must allow authorities to intercept electronic information pursuant to=
 a court order. It couldn=E2=80=99t be determined if systems that support f=
oreign intelligence surveillance were also vulnerable in the breach=E2=80=
=A6A person familiar with the attack said the U.S. government considered th=
e intrusions to be historically significant and worrisome.

You might have noticed that the title of this section of the Update uses th=
e passive voice; the reason is because the subject of an active voice isn=
=E2=80=99t as clear as you might think. In a narrow sense, the subject shou=
ld be China: =E2=80=9CChina Hacks U.S. Communications=E2=80=9D. That is cer=
tainly what has happened here.

The History of CALEA
--------------------

In truth, though, this hack happened a long time time ago. The first possib=
le date is 1994, and the entity at fault is the U.S. Congress. That is when=
 the =E2=80=9CCommunications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act (CALEA)=E2=
=80=9D was passed.

It used to be that a wiretap involved, well, tapping a wire. Law enforcemen=
t would gain physical access to a phone line and attach a device to capture=
 the audio of phone conversations. This was possible because the way teleph=
ones used to work is that they would convert audio into an analog electrica=
l signal, which would be converted back into audio by the recipient telepho=
ne. The intervening analog signal, though, wasn=E2=80=99t encrypted; any de=
vice could reconvert it back into audio.

The telephone system doesn=E2=80=99t work like that anymore, as you might e=
xpect; your device does convert audio into an analog electrical signal, but=
 it then further converts that analog electrical signal into a digital sign=
al =E2=80=94 1s and 0s, basically, which can be encrypted.

Encryption, however, can mean multiple things; I discussed the distinction =
between end-to-end encryption and transport layer encryption this summer in=
 the context of the Telegram case ( https://stratechery.com/2024/telegram-c=
eo-arrested-telegrams-non-encrypted-advantage-telegram-complexities/?access=
_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS=
IsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAi=
OiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWN=
oZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L3RlbGVncmFtLWNlby1hcnJlc3RlZC10ZWxlZ3JhbXMtbm9uLWVuY3J5cH=
RlZC1hZHZhbnRhZ2UtdGVsZWdyYW0tY29tcGxleGl0aWVzLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzMwODg2NDE3L=
CJpYXQiOjE3MjgyOTQ0MTcsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0=
aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJ=
lYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6Im=
FjY2VzcyJ9.UkkeDKzP5J9p4aNYoQZcb0aX7AUjC09-fDIVte2SNfLkZ3zt771VABo16FjJayvC=
EnPi0CmDv4gR_B1CmxNDP0IDBqjdKrKO4IlnDzDq_bUjvG-UxCJm_dZ6ZCSYXuR0AYgKioNbSK4=
ecg0OH7I8rCM5OJkMUSfWS2iOHMimUppOccNp1Sk03P0vvn1zRiByDiFQukzAZ1qsB3RIU_D_db=
bpMOffWxoQt93Yx3gb4uvityVH89LWdZrP9vz05aO98x_oj1Bxn5RNCsS1_U6WVUQ-9lGNfDPDg=
VemWgaTHyLsy2gCFvwyhYHDVrUPVlpoNCznQuQnhKke-x9N114LNQ ) , but in short:

* End-to-end encryption means the digital signal is encrypted on the origin=
ating device using a key known only to the device owner, and can only be de=
crypted by the recipient on their device using the corresponding public key=
 for the originator=E2=80=99s private key.
* Transport layer encryption means the digital signal is encrypted on the o=
riginating device using a key granted (or at least known) by the service re=
ceiving the communications; that signal can then be decrypted by the servic=
e once it arrives. It is, however, encrypted in transit.

Transport layer encryption is the standard for most digital communications;=
 your communication between your device and the server you are accessing, w=
hether that be an e-commerce site, a site like Stratechery, or a communicat=
ions service, is generally safe from so-called =E2=80=9CMan-in-the-middle (=
MITM)=E2=80=9D attacks, where a third-party captures your communication and=
 interferes with it in some way.

Notice, though, that old-school wiretapping is a canonical man-in-the-middl=
e attack: law enforcement is =E2=80=94 again, literally =E2=80=94 tapping t=
he wire you are using to communicate and listening in. Law enforcement rath=
er likes this ability, and was concerned about losing this capability in th=
e transition to digital signals.

Thus was born CALEA: Congress mandated that communications providers =E2=80=
=94 who remember, are providing the keys for transport layer encryption =E2=
=80=94 create the capability for law enforcement to listen in on conversati=
ons, i.e. leverage their control of encryption keys to give access to the u=
nderlying data. This is the capability that was leveraged in these attacks,=
 so it=E2=80=99s not wrong to say that =E2=80=9CCongress Hacked U.S. Commun=
ications=E2=80=9D, by creating this capability in the first place.

It=E2=80=99s also not entirely right; CALEA actually expressly excluded dat=
a. The goal was to recreate the ability to wiretap voice calls, not to expa=
nd surveillance. Moreover, phone calls, even as they became digital, still =
worked differently than the Internet.

That last part would soon change. In the decade after CALEA was passed it i=
ncreasingly made more sense to simply treat voice digital signals the same =
as other digital signals, using Voice-over-IP (VoIP). Now everything was pa=
ckets of 1s and 0s, and restricting CALEA to only voice both became more te=
chnically challenging and somewhat nonsensical; meanwhile, law enforcement =
agencies were making the case that more and more criminal communication was=
 happening through means other than voice.

To that end, in 2004, the DOJ, ATF, FBI, and DEA filed a petition with the =
FCC to expand CALEA to cover all IP traffic, including broadband Internet c=
ommunications; the FCC did so, and when challenged in court, won ( https://=
docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/DOC-266204A1.pdf ) thanks to the Chevron de=
ference doctrine, which granted substantial law-making ability to agencies =
in lieu of explicit Congressional directions. In this case specifically the=
 court held that Congress=E2=80=99s explicit exclusion of =E2=80=9Cinformat=
ion services=E2=80=9D did not necessarily apply to broadband, which frankly=
, still confuses me; indeed, this case is one of the stronger arguments aga=
inst Chevron, which was overturned earlier this year.

Regardless, the pertinent takeaway for this Article is that you can argue t=
hat the =E2=80=9CFCC Hacked U.S. Communications=E2=80=9D, and the reason is=
 this: yes, the Chinese hacked into U.S. communications, but they did so vi=
a a backdoor mandated by CALEA, which was expanded to include internet comm=
unications by the FCC. Without CALEA and without that 2004 expansion there =
would not have been a vulnerability for the Chinese to hack.

Encryption and Backdoors
------------------------

This case is another manifestation of the age-old debate about encryption a=
nd backdoors that has more recently flared up in the context of end-to-end =
encryption. Many in tech, including myself, resolutely oppose any attempt t=
o create backdoors in end-to-end encryption, even while admitting the trade=
-offs that entails.

This case explains why: backdoors can and will, in the fullness of time, be=
 hacked. The only way to guarantee true privacy in communications is end-to=
-end encryption; compromising that may make it easier to catch criminals, b=
ut it also puts everyone at risk from other =E2=80=94 often worse =E2=80=94=
 bad actors.

That=E2=80=99s exactly what happened here. There is obviously an argument f=
or wire-tapping, and it is definitely the case that wire-tapping became muc=
h more difficult and complicated with the shift to digital. The arguments f=
or CALEA are clear, and even for the FCC=E2=80=99s expansion to broadband (=
even if the legal justification is less clear). The insertion of those back=
doors into every U.S. telecommunications provider, though, meant the creati=
on of a vulnerability in communications for everyone, the exploitation of w=
hich was only a question of time. That time has arrived, via Chinese hacker=
s; they=E2=80=99re to blame for this mess, but not the only ones.

